the ovum","Muscular sphincters that control ovum transport"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fimbriae are specialised structures at the distal (ovarian) end of the fallopian tubes that play a crucial role in reproduction. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efinger-like projections with ciliated epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E create gentle sweeping movements that help capture and guide the ovum into the fallopian tube after ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle projections that contract to move the ovum\u003C/strong\u003E are present in the fallopian tube to aid ovum transport through peristalsis, however this is not the primary function of the fimbriae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretory cells that produce hormones to attract the ovum\u003C/strong\u003E produce fluid to nourish the ovum and sperm but this is not the primary function of the fimbriae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnective tissue bands that anchor the ovary\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The ovary is held in place by other ligamentous structures such as the suspensory ligament and the ovarian ligament, not by the fimbriae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscular sphincters that control ovum transport\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The fallopian tube does not contain sphincters; transport is achieved through ciliary action and peristalsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fimbriae are part of the infundibulum of the fallopian tube and are essential for fertility. Their coordinated movement with ciliated epithelium creates a current in the peritoneal fluid that helps direct the ovum into the fallopian tube where fertilisation typically occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fimbriae are finger-like projections at the distal end of the fallopian tube that capture and guide the ovum into the tube.","The fimbriae are lined with ciliated epithelium that helps transport the ovum towards the uterus.","The fimbriated end of the fallopian tube is also known as the infundibulum."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Schlafer DH, Foster RA. Female Genital System. Jubb, Kennedy \u0026 Palmer\u0027s Pathology of Domestic Animals: Volume 3. 2016:358\u2013464.e1. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-7020-5319-1.00015-3. Epub 2016 Mar 18. PMCID: PMC7158333.","Rosner J, Samardzic T, Sarao MS. Physiology, Female Reproduction. [Updated 2024 Mar 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537132/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57067"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15701"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57067"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T15:17:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T21:00:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71571"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":